For example, the permutation [1,3,4,5,2,6,7,...] has a descent at position 4 (5 > 2), so it can be split into [1,3,4,5] and [2,6,7,...]. However, in order for the first pass to take the first increasing sequence and the remaining to form another, the descent must be such that the first sequence is increasing and the remaining is also increasing. Wait, but in the example permutation [1,3,4,5,2,6,7,...], the first pass would take 1,3,4,5 (since they are increasing), then the remaining numbers are 2,6,7,... which are not necessarily increasing.
